m -- tIX. About how Diego de Almagro returned to Panama, where he found that Pedrarias was recruiting people for Nicaragua, and what happened to him as well as his partner, Captain Francisco Pizarro -- tX. About how Pizarro and Almagro journeyed as far as the San Juan River, where it was agreed that the pilot, Bartolome Ruiz would explore along the western coast and Almagro would return for more people -- tXI. How when the Spaniards went in canoes looking for provisions, all the Spaniards who went with their Captain Varela in one of the canoes were killed by the Indians -- tXII. About how Pedro de los Rios came as governor to Tierra Firme and what Almagro did in Panama until he returned with people -- tXIII. About how the captains and the Spaniards embarked and sailed to Atacames, and what happened to them -- tXIV. About how all the Spaniards wanted to return to Panama and could not, and how Diego de Almagro departed with the ships while Pizarro remained on Gallo Island, and about the couplet that they sent to Governor Pedro de los Rios -- tXV. About how when Diego de Almagro arrived in Panama, Governor Pedro de los Rios, distressed by the death of so many people, did not allow him to recruit more. And how [Rios] sent Juan Tafur to set free the Spaniards, and what Pizarro did with the letters his partners had sent him -- tXVI. About how Juan Tafur arrived where the Christians were and how they were set free, all of them wanting to return, except thirteen; and they and Pizarro remained -- tXVII. About how Captain Francisco Pizarro remained on the deserted island and of the many things he and his companions endured, and about the arrival of the ships in Panama -- tXVIII. About how Juan Tafur arrived in Panama and how one ship returned to Gorgona to Captain Francisco Pizarro -- tXIX. About how Captain Francisco Pizarro and his companions left the island and what they did -- tXX. About how the Indians who left the ship reported about the Spaniards, which those from the land marveled at, and how they sent them provisions and water and other things -- tXXI. About how the captain ordered Pedro de Candia to go and see whether what Alonso de Molina said he saw in the land of Tumbez was true -- tXXII. About how Captain Francisco Pizarro continued the discovery and what happened to him -- tXXIII. About how Captain Francisco Pizarro turned around and landed in some Indian villages, where things went well for him, and what else happened to him -- tXXIV. About how the captain took possession of those lands and what else he did until he left them -- tXXV. How Pizarro arrived in Panama, where he tried to negotiate with Pedro de los Rios to grant him people to return with, but because it did not happen, he decided to go to Spain -- tXXVI. About how Captain Francisco Pizarro went to Spain to report to the emperor about the land he had discovered, and what Almagro did in Tierra Firme -- tXXVII. About how Captain Francisco Pizarro arrived in Spain and was given the governance of Peru -- tXXVIII. About how the Governor Don Francisco Pizarro returned to Tierra Firme, having first sent certain Spaniards in a ship to report on what he had negotiated -- tXXIX. About how the Governor Don Francisco Pizarro arrived at Nombre de Dios and what occurred between him and Diego de Almagro; and how in Panama they renewed their friendship and formed a new partnership -- tXXX. About how Governor Don Francisco Pizarro left Panama and Captain Diego de Almagro stayed there, and how Pizarro entered Coaque -- tXXXI. About how Pizarro decided to send ships to Panama and Nicaragua with the gold that was found, and how some Christians came to join him, and about how many became ill -- tXXXII. About how [Pizarro] proceeded on his march, and [the Indians] killed two of his Christians, and Belalcazar arrived with other Christians from Nicaragua, and what else happened -- tXXXIII. About how the governor proceeded on his march and there was great discontent among the Spaniards, and about how messengers came from Puna, [saying] that the islanders were determined to kill our men -- tXXXIV. About how those of the island still planned to kill the Spaniards, and Tumbala was imprisoned, and how the islanders fought with our men -- tXXXV. About how those of Puna and their allies fought a battle with the Christians, in which [the Indians] were defeated, and what else happened -- tXXXVI. About how those of Tumbez held secret councils [to discuss] whether they would remain friendly with the Christians or come out against them as enemies, and how they killed two Spaniards, having decided to kill all of them if they could -- tXXXVII. How Pizarro, having arrived in Tumbez wanted to punish the Indians for killing the two Christians, and what else happened -- tXXXVIII. About how Pizarro left Tumbez and arrived at Solana, from where Soto and Belalcazar left with people for the highlands, and how the city of San Miguel was founded -- tXXXIX. About how when the people who escaped from the battle were collected, Huascar's captains made more exhortations, and a third battle was fought in the Jauja Valley, which was very bloody; and about how Atahualpa remained in Cajamarca -- tXL. About how there was another battle between them, and Huascar left Cu~co and was seized through deception -- tXLI. About how Pizarro set out from the new settlement he had established in order to ascend into the highlands in search of Atahualpa -- tXLII. About how Atahualpa was informed how near he was to the Spaniards, and about the council he held, and how he sent messengers to Pizarro that he should not cease marching -- tXLIII. About how Pizarro and the Spaniards took up quarters in Cajamarca, and how Soto went to Atahualpa's camp, and what else happened -- tXLIV. About what Atahualpa told his people before they moved from where they were, and how one of the Christians came to talk to him -- tXLV. About how Atahualpa entered the plaza where the Christians were, and how he was seized and many of his people were killed and wounded -- tXLVI. About how in the morning of the following day the Spaniards went to survey the countryside, and how the news of Atahualpa's capture spread throughout the entire realm -- tXLVII. About how Almagro set out on ships from Panama to Peru to aid Pizarro and what happened to him -- tXLVIII. About how Atahualpa promised the Spaniards a great treasure as his ransom, and about the death of King Huascar -- tXLIX. How the three Christians who went to Cu~co arrived in that city and what happened to them; and how by Pizarro's order his brother Hernando Pizarro left Cajamarca to get the treasure of the Temple of Pachacamac -- tL. About how Almagro and his people entered Cajamarca, where he was well received by those who were there, and about what happened to Hernando Pizarro during the journey to Pachacamac -- tLI. About how keeping the promise he had made to the Spaniards, Atahualpa filled the house with treasure, and how those who came with Almagro claimed shares like those who were there first -- tLII. 00tAbout how the great treasure that had been collected in Cajamarca by the order of the great lord Atahualpa was divided among the Spaniards and the names of all the Christians who were present at his capture -- tLIII. How after the treasure was divided, Pizarro decided that his brother Hernando Pizarro should go with the news to the emperor -- tLIV. About how false news came that warriors were advancing against the Spaniards, and about how Pizarro, breaking the word and the contract that he made with Atahualpa, put him to death with great cruelty and little justice -- tLV. About what else happened in Cajamarca after Atahualpa died, and how Soto returned without seeing or encountering any warriors -- tLVI. About how Pizarro left Cajamarca for the city of Cuzco and what happened to him until he arrived in the Jauja Valley -- tLVII. About how Sebastian de Belalcazar arrived in the city of San Miguel and how, desirous to explore Quito, he negotiated with the cabildo to request him to go against the warriors who were said to be coming against them -- tLVIII. About how Belalcazar defeated a captain they had sent against him, and the natives were delighted to see the Christians when they arrived in Tomebamba, and they formed a friendship with them, and about how the captains of Quito went out to wage war against them -- tLIX. About what else happened to the Spaniards and the Indians until they reached the tableland of Riobamba, where [the Indians] had dug many pits so that the horses would fall into them -- tLX. How a volcano or a mouth of fire erupted near Quito and what happened to the Christians and the Indians -- tLXI. About how Governor Don Francisco Pizarro founded a city in the Jauja Valley, which is the one that was later moved to the Lima Valley, and about the death of the Inca and other things that happened -- tLXII. About how the Indians waited to battle the Christians in the highlands of Vilcaconga, and how when Soto arrived, they fought each other and what happened until Almagro and several horsemen came to their rescue -- tLXIII. About how the Adelantado Don Pedro de Alvarado, governor of Guatemala, left the port of La Posesion in order to come with a great fleet to this kingdom -- tLXIV. About what the Spaniards whom Pizarro sent from Jauja to the coast of the South Sea were doing -- tLXV. About how Adelantado Don Pedro de Alvarado decided to go to Quito and about some notable things that happened to him -- tLXVI. About how the adelantado ordered people to go out and find a road, and about how they encountered many marshes and rivers, and how several Spaniards died, among them Captain Don Juan Enriquez de Guzman -- tLXVII. About the things that further happened to the adelantado, and about the great hardships and needs that his people suffered -- tLXVIII. About how Pizarro marched on the way to Cuzco, ordering that Atahualpa's captain-general, Chalcuchima, be burned in the valley of Jaquijahuana, and about other notable things that happened -- tLXIX. About how the Spaniards entered the ancient city of Cuzco, where they found great treasures and precious things -- tLXX. About how Ruminavi abandoned the city of Quito, first killing many principal women so that they could not be enjoyed by the Christians, who were very upset when they entered in it and did not see the treasure they sought, and what else happened -- tLXXI. About what happened in the city of Cuzco, and about how Almagro and Hernando de Soto went out against the Indians, and Gabriel de Rojas arrived -- tLXXII. How Adelantado Alvarado arrived in the village discovered by Diego de Alvarado, who had left to explore and came upon some snow covered mountain passes, and about the hardship that the Spaniards suffered -- tLXXIII. How Adelantado Alvarado went with great hardship through the snow, where some Spaniards and many Indian men and women and Blacks died, unable to escape the cold, wind, and snow, which was enough to kill them -- tLXXIV. How Captain Belalcazar returned with his people to Quito, from where Almagro departed, and how certain scouts that [Almagro] sent were seized by Diego de Alvarado -- tLXXV. How Almagro learned that his scouts were captured, and how he founded a city in Riobamba, and they went to enjoin the adelantado, and what else happened between them -- tLXXVI. About how Adelantado Don Pedro de Alvarado and Marshal Don Diego de Almagro met, and about the agreement made between them, guided and steered by Licentiate Caldera and other judicious men who came with the adelantado -- tLXXVII. About how Soto and Gabriel de Rojas arrived in Cuzco, and how Pizarro left that city and the things that he did until he descended to the plains after abandoning the city of Jauja -- tLXXVIII. How Pizarro was falsely informed that Almagro had agreed to divest him of his governance and life, and how after some notable things occurred, they arrived at Pachacamac, and what else happened until the City of the Kings was founded -- tLXXIX. About how Hernando Pizarro arrived in Spain, where great news about Peru was spreading because of how much wealth was coming from there, and what Hernando Pizarro did at court -- tLXXX. About how His Majesty granted Hernando Pizarro the Order of Santiago, and how he departed from court and embarked for the Indies -- tLXXXI. How Almagro set out from Pachacamac for Cuzco, from where Pizarro left a few days later to found Trujillo in the Chimu Valley -- tLXXXII. About how Don Francisco Pizarro sent Verdugo to Cuzco with powers for his brother Juan Pizarro to have the lieutenancy of the city, and about the discussions that took place there, and what else happened -- tLXXXIII. About how Don Francisco Pizarro returned to the City of the Kings, then left to go to the city of Cuzco when he learned of the things that were happening there -- tLXXXIV. About how the governors reached a new accord, making a solemn oath to proceed with the partnership -- tLXXXV. About how Almagro spent a large sum of gold and silver on those who were to go, and how he departed from Cuzco -- tLXXXVI. About how Pizarro left Cuzco to return to the City of the Kings -- tLXXXVII. About how Belalcazar moved the city of Riobamba to Quito, and about what happened in that land -- tLXXXVIII. About how wanting to make a founding in the City of the Kings, they waited until Hernando Pizarro arrived, and how the bishop of Tierra Firme and others who were rich left from the port -- tLXXXIX. About how Alonso de Alvarado left Trujillo to settle a city in Chachapoyas -- tXC. About how while Juan Pizarro was lieutenant and captain in Cuzco, King Manco Inca Yupanqui, detesting the rule the Christians had over them, attempted to leave the city in order to begin a war against them and was seized twice and placed in chains -- tXCI. About how after killing a Spaniard, those who killed him fortified themselves on a ridge top with their cacique, and about what happened until the ridge top was taken -- tXCII. About how a founding was done in the City of the Kings and Hernando Pizarro procured that the said donation be of fired to His Majesty, and about his parting for Cuzco and the governor's departure to inspect the northern cities -- tXCIII. About what happened to Captain Alonso de Alvarado in his conquest of the Chachapoyas -- tXCIV. About how Almagro sent Captain Salcedo to punish the Indians who had killed the three Christians, and they gave him a gift of more than ninety thousand pesos, and how Villac Umu fled, and what else happened -- tXCV. About how, while exploring, Almagro arrived at snowy mountain passes where his people suffered great hardship -- tXCVI. About how Rodrigo Orgonos left Cuzco and what happened to him until he reached the valley of Copiapo -- tXCVII. About how Juan de Herrada left Cuzco to take the decrees to Almagro, and what happened to him until he reached the valley of Copiapo, where he joined Orgonos -- tXCVIII. That Hernando Pizarro, upon reaching Cuzco freed Inca Manco, who left the city and started the war -- tXCIX. That the fortress of Cuzco was won and Juan Pizarro died then; Hernando Pizarro marched on Tambo -- tC. That the war with the Indians continues and Gabriel de Rojas routs an enemy army -- tCI. 00tThat the Adelantado Don Diego de Almagro gives up the Chilean enterprise and returns to Cuzco, and what happened with Manco Inca Yupanqui -- tMaps -- tGlossary -- tWeights, Measures, and Currency -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tABOUT THE AUTHORS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDazzled by the sight of the vast treasure of gold and silver being unloaded at Seville's docks in 1537, a teenaged Pedro de Cieza de León vowed to join the Spanish effort in the New World, become an explorer, and write what would become the earliest historical account of the conquest of Peru. Available for the first time in English, this history of Peru is based largely on interviews with Cieza's conquistador compatriates, as well as with Indian informants knowledgeable of the Incan past.Alexandra Parma Cook and Noble David Cook present this recently discovered third book of a four-part chronicle that provides the most thorough and definitive record of the birth of modern Andean America. It describes with unparalleled detail the exploration of the Pacific coast of South America led by Francisco Pizarro and Diego de Almagro, the imprisonment and death of the Inca Atahualpa, the Indian resistance, and the ultimate Spanish domination.Students and scholars of Latin American history and conquest narratives will welcome the publication of this volume.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh1 aCook, Alexandra Parma1 aCook, Noble David08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822382508zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822382508423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822382508.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles